Sasalin spewed a jet of flame, the tall Slak burning a small patch of forest before circling overhead, watching for the right moment. Strangely, when he slowed down, the eerie screeching behind him also ceased. Sasalin had forgotten there was a passenger on his back.
"C'mon, Tenuk, you've transformed into a Slack person before!"
"Going on your own and suddenly being dragged away by a huge pink dragon are two different things!"
"Alright, Kael?"
Clearly disagreeing with Nishi, Kayer looked paler than usual, his claws digging deeply into Sasarin's back, drawing blood from the Slackers. Yet, Sasarin evidently didn't seem to mind. That said, Sasarin realized he had frightened his new friend and found an open area to land.
"Sorry, sorry, I smelled something. I need to take care of it!"
"You had to drag us along too?" Tenuk climbed down from Sasarin's back, sliding down the tail to the ground, and asked sharply. "We left Retwick behind! We abandoned that strong, quarrelsome brute! How is he ever going to find us?"
"He'll figure it out somehow..." Nishi nodded. "Retvik may be slow, but he's not stupid."
"Does Rettvik know how to drive?"
Nix blinked and turned his head to look at Tenok. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Rettwick drive a car? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've never seen him drive a cute little car like Kayel's. He started taking the car to work purely because you always drove us to work. He only has a bicycle."
A burst of laughter interrupted them. Sasalin suddenly burst into uncontrollable laughter, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took Sasalin a long time before he could calm down.
"Sorry, sorry, I just imagined it for a moment—your big, armored friend riding a small bicycle designed specifically for children from Thomson. That scene is so ridiculous! I really wish I had telepathy. This idea is so funny! I definitely need to treasure it!"
Kayer also smiled because he could imagine what Sasalin was thinking. "Alright, alright. But what exactly did you smell? Why did you fly so fast?"
Sasarin grunted, quickly disappeared after taking off, then flew back and dropped a corpse in front of Nishi. It was an Orothsalak, a very rare golden-white dragon-like creature. But its head was missing. "Another one has died. I heard their cries. I smelled their blood. I must protect them and hunt down the killer. This is the will of Isini. Those creatures are nearby."
The powerful Slack suddenly froze. Nishi and Kayer also froze, their attention drawn to a gap at the edge of the open ground. A huge, pitch-black creature was staring at them, hissing. The creature suddenly spread its two pairs of massive wings and charged forward, directly at Sasarin, completely ignoring the three small figures standing in its path. Kayer and Tenuk barely managed to dodge aside, but Nishi found himself thrown to the ground, nearly flung onto Sasarin.
Sasalin seized Nishi by the arm, flung her onto his back with his long and nimble tail, and then took to the air. The black creature with two pairs of wings quickly gave chase.
Kayer muttered, drew his rifle from behind, opened the bag, and took out a belt of bullets. He fastened the belt across his chest for easy access, but quickly realized that Nishi, Sasarin, and the creature were gone.
"Hey, Tenuk, can you transform into a flying animal?" asked Kayer.
"Do you want to chase after him?"
"Nonsense."
"But... one of them is a giant monster!"
"So what? This rifle in my hands is powerful and I can fire anytime. I just need to see it, and I can shoot it down."
Tenuk hesitated for a moment, then stepped back to create some space. With a low, slightly pained groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turning into scales, his arms transforming into wings. Soon, he became an ordinary light-blue Slake, but his eyes remained red.
"Come up."
Tenuk now looked like an ordinary Slack, with neatly arranged scale armor growing along his back and a pair of sharp spines that made it easier for Kayer to grab hold of him. It took Tenuk a long time to get airborne, but once he was up, he quickly adjusted his direction and struggled to catch up.
However, Tenok and Kayer quickly realized they were not facing just one opponent. A second dark creature emerged from beneath them, and Tenok barely managed to dodge the impact.
"I guess this is the other terrifying monster that Ranecks was worried about?" Kayel furrowed his brow, trying to shoot the second monster but missed, then quickly reloaded his weapon.
Tennok didn't respond; he was too busy flying toward Nishi and Sasarin, even though another monster was chasing them. Kayel awkwardly turned around to face the monster. As it pursued them, Kayel saw this as good news because it made him easier to aim and shoot at. Two bullets pierced the monster's upper wing, and it howled in pain before disappearing into the forest. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still following them, but he felt confident that it couldn't keep up anymore.
Ahead, Sasalin was wildly flailing his body, spewing flames at the black monster, while Nishi desperately clung to Sasalin to prevent himself from falling. Although the monster was definitely injured, it seemed enraged and unwilling to retreat, and the fireballs appeared to have caused only minimal damage. After Sasalin steadied himself, Nishi seized the opportunity to pull out his weapon—a shotgun he trusted. Of course, a shotgun wouldn't be effective against a creature like this, but the spread of bullets might at least scare off the black beast?
